    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Westerly Winds Bring a Brown Fall</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harold L Newmark letter questions whether toxic effects of 'acid rain' pollutants could be major contributor to early browning of leaves in New England states</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Leaf-Proud New England Braces for a Brownish Fall'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Leaf-Proud New England Braces for a Brownish Fall'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>In addition to the drought and the unusually hot summer, the prevailing west wind over the Middle Atlantic states and New England brings increased levels of nitrogen oxides and sulfur oxides.</p>
        <p>These air pollutants largely come from older coal-burning power plants in the Ohio Valley, which are not equipped with scrubbers to remove toxic components in their exhaust.</p>
        <p>The toxic effects of these ''acid rain'' pollutants in New England and Canadian forests have long been recognized. Could they also be a major contributor to the early ''browning'' of leaves and to the increase  in asthma in children and the elderly?</p>
        <p>HAROLD L. NEWMARK  Piscataway, N.J., Aug. 19, 1999</p>
        <p>The writer is a researcher in cancer prevention at Rutgers University.</p>
      </block>
